{{About|the novel|the television series|Aşk-ı Memnu (TV series)}} {{infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = The Forbidden Love | title_orig = Aşk-ı Memnu | translator = | image = Ask-i Memnu.jpg | author = [[Halit Ziya Uşaklıgil]] | cover_artist = | country = [[Turkey]] | language = [[Turkish language|Turkish]] | series = | genre = | publisher = Nilüfer | release_date = 1899 | media_type = | pages = | preceded_by = | }}
'''''Aşk-ı Memnu''''' ({{IPA-tr|aʃkˌɯ memˈnuː}}) ([[Ottoman Turkish language|Ottoman Turkish]] for ''The Forbidden Love'') is a [[Turkey|Turkish]] romance novel by [[Halit Ziya Uşaklıgil]]. It was serialized in 1899 and 1900 in'' [[Servet-i Fünun]]'', a leading Turkish literary magazine of the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yenimakale.com/halit-ziya-usakligilin-ask-i-memnu-romani.html|title=Halit Ziya Uşaklıgil'in "Aşk-ı Memnu" Romanı|publisher=Yeni Makale|date=1 October 2014|language=Turkish}}</ref>
==Adaptations== ''Aşk-ı Memnu'' was adapted by [[Halit Refiğ]] into a TV series in 1975, considered to be the first miniseries on Turkish television. Another TV series adaptation named ''[[Aşk-ı Memnu (TV series)|Aşk-ı Memnu]]'' aired from 2008 to 2010. It takes place in the modern-day Istanbul instead of the novel's late 19th-century setting. The novel is again being adapted as a Spanish TV series based on the Turkish serial adaption. It will be produced by Telemundo. The novel was made into a 3-act play by Tarık Günersel, who also wrote a libretto for the Turkish composer Selman Ada leading to an opera.
==References== <references /> {{Turkey-stub}}
{{DEFAULTSORT:Ask-I Memnu}} [[Category:1900 novels]] [[Category:Turkish novels]] [[Category:Novels first published in serial form]] [[Category:Works originally published in Turkish magazines]] [[Category:Works originally published in literary magazines]] [[Category:Novels set in Istanbul]]

The '''Berner Bach-Chor''' is a [[Swiss people|Swiss]] [[choir]] based in [[Bern]], Switzerland. It is described as "a dynamic choir with one [[concert]] activity; a choir, openly for unusual, unknown and contemporary; a choir with international radiant emittance; an inspired community of approximately 120 [[singer]]s; a choir, which was distinguished for its qualitatively high standing of work in 1997 with the culture prize of the [[Bürgergemeinde]] Bern."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Bio/Berner-Bach-Chor.htm|title=Berner Bach-Chor (Choir)|publisher=Bach Cantatas|accessdate=}}</ref>

The choir was founded by Theo Loosli,<ref name="FuhrimannSymphonieorchester2002">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_80XAQAAIAAJ|title=Wechselklänge: die Bernische Musikgesellschaft 1960-2000 : Festschrift zum 125-jährigen Bestehen des Berner Symphonie-Orchesters (1877-2002)|last2=Symphonieorchester|first2=Berner|publisher=Stämpfli|year=2002|isbn=978-3-7272-1164-5|page=173|last1=Fuhrimann|first1=Daniel|accessdate=3 October 2012}}</ref> and is currently being [[Conductor (music)|conducted]] by Lena-Lisa Wüstendörfer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bachchor.ch/Chor/Chor|title=Bach Chor Bern|website=www.bachchor.ch|language=en|access-date=2017-03-18}}</ref>

