{{Infobox book <!-- |italic title = (see above) --> | name = Docherty | image = | image_size = | border = | caption = | alt = | author = [[William McIlvanney]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | subject = | genre = | publisher = [[Allen & Unwin]] | publisher2 = | pub_date = {{Start date|1975|02|06|df=y}} | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 320 | awards = | isbn = 9780048231185 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | preceded_by_quotation_marks = | followed_by = | followed_by_quotation_marks = | wikisource = }}
'''''Docherty''''' is the third novel by [[William McIlvanney]], first published in 1975.<ref name=list>{{cite web|title=100 Best Scottish Books of all Time|url=http://www.list.co.uk/article/2754-william-mcilvanney-docherty-1975/|publisher=[[The List (magazine)|The List]]|accessdate=30 July 2013}}</ref>
==Plot== The book is set in a fictional mining town in Scotland in the early part of the 20th century, and it relates the struggles of a miner called Tam Docherty and his family.
==Background== McIlvanney said the novel was "an attempt to democratise traditional culture, to give [[working-class]] life the vote in the literature of heroism."<ref>Hammond, Andrew. ''British Fiction and the Cold War'', London: Palgrave Macmillan, 2013</ref>
==Awards== * [[1975 Whitbread Awards|1975]] [[Whitbread Book Awards|Whitbread Award, for Best Novel]] <ref name=IrishTimes_Honour>{{cite news|last=Dening|first=Penelope|title=Honour in his own country|newspaper=The Irish Times|date=1 October 1996}}</ref> *1975 [[Scottish Arts Council]] Book Award<ref>{{cite web|title=William McIlvanney - Literature|url=https://literature.britishcouncil.org/writer/william-mcilvanney|website=literature.britishcouncil.org|accessdate=24 January 2017|language=en}}</ref>
